## Impact on Abortion Providers and Patients

### Effect on Providers

- **Legal Exposure:** Providers face the risk of multiple lawsuits with significant financial penalties, even if they successfully defend themselves ([Ivey, 2021](https://www.contemporaryobgyn.net/view/texas-senate-bill-8-sb-8-not-just-another-anti-abortion-bill)).

- **Insurance and Institutional Support:** Most medical malpractice insurers and hospitals have declined to cover legal defense costs related to SB 8 lawsuits ([Ivey, 2021](https://www.contemporaryobgyn.net/view/texas-senate-bill-8-sb-8-not-just-another-anti-abortion-bill)).

- **Chilling Effect:** The threat of litigation has led many providers to cease offering abortions beyond six weeks, even where exceptions might apply ([Planned Parenthood Greater Texas, 2021](https://www.plannedparenthood.org/planned-parenthood-greater-texas)).

### Effect on Patients

- **Access Limitations:** Since many pregnancies are not detected until after six weeks, the law effectively bans most abortions in Texas ([CDC, 2019](https://www.cdc.gov/reproductivehealth/data_stats/abortion.htm)).

- **No Liability for Patients:** Patients cannot be sued under SB 8, but those assisting them can be ([Robinson, 2021](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-09-01/how-the-new-texas-abortion-law-turns-the-public-into-enforcers)).

- **Travel and Financial Burden:** Patients often must travel out of state for abortion care, incurring significant costs and logistical challenges, disproportionately affecting low-income and marginalized populations ([Ivey, 2021](https://www.contemporaryobgyn.net/view/texas-senate-bill-8-sb-8-not-just-another-anti-abortion-bill)).

- **Parental Consent for Minors:** Minors require parental consent or judicial bypass to obtain an abortion, with no exceptions for the six-week ban ([ACLU Texas, 2021](https://www.aclutx.org/en/know-your-rights/abortion-texas)).

