## Comparison with Previous Texas Abortion Laws and U.S. Supreme Court Precedents

| Aspect                      | SB 8 (2021)                                  | Previous Texas Laws (e.g., HB 2)                   | U.S. Supreme Court Precedent (Roe v. Wade, Planned Parenthood v. Casey) |
|-----------------------------|----------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| **Gestational Limit**        | ~6 weeks (heartbeat detection)               | Varied; often 20-24 weeks or based on viability   | Abortion protected until viability (~24 weeks)                         |
| **Enforcement**              | Private civil lawsuits only                    | State enforcement by officials                     | State enforcement with constitutional protections                      |
| **Exceptions**               | Medical emergency only; no rape/incest/fetal anomaly exceptions | Some exceptions allowed                            | Exceptions required for rape, incest, and health of the mother         |
| **Legal Challenges**         | Pre-enforcement challenges blocked by unique enforcement | Pre-enforcement challenges allowed                 | Pre-enforcement challenges standard                                   |
| **Impact on Providers**      | High risk of litigation and financial penalties | Clinic closures due to admitting privileges and facility requirements | Protections against undue burdens on providers                        |

SB 8 represents a significant departure from prior abortion restrictions and Supreme Court rulings by effectively banning abortions before viability and using a private enforcement mechanism to avoid judicial review ([Laws101, 2021](https://laws101.com/texas-abortion-laws); [Robinson, 2021](https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2021-09-01/how-the-new-texas-abortion-law-turns-the-public-into-enforcers)).

